! Kin Filter Gotchas

The `[kin[]]` filter (by bimlas) traverses parent-child trees. Syntax: `[kin:<field>:<direction>:<depth>[<operand>]]`.

!! 1. Direction semantics are relative to the field, not the tree

`from` follows the field value (child→parent), `to` finds things pointing to this title via the field (parent→children), `with` is both.

```
<!-- To find DESCENDANTS of a node (children, grandchildren, etc.) via parent field: -->
[kin:parent:to[MyNode]]

<!-- NOT: -->
[kin:parent:from[MyNode]]
<!-- ^^^ this finds ANCESTORS (parent, grandparent, etc.) -->
```

Mnemonic: `to` means "titles pointing TO this one via the field" = descendants. `from` means "where this title's field points FROM" = ancestors.

!! 2. The base title is always included in results

`[kin:parent:to[MyNode]]` returns MyNode itself plus all descendants. To exclude the base:

```
[kin:parent:to[MyNode]] -[<myNode>]
```

!! 3. Depth parameter is 1-indexed, 0 means unlimited

`[kin:parent:to:1[MyNode]]` returns MyNode + its direct children (depth 1). There is no way to say "only depth 1 without the base" in a single operator — subtract the base separately.

`[kin:parent:to:0[MyNode]]` and `[kin:parent:to[MyNode]]` are identical — both traverse the full tree.

!! 4. Global cache — results can go stale

The kin filter caches results globally per (baseTitle, fieldName, direction) tuple. The cache persists for the wiki session. If tiddlers are created/deleted/reparented, cached kin results may be stale until wiki reload.

```
<!-- After creating a new child of MyNode, [kin:parent:to[MyNode]]
     may NOT include the new child until the page is refreshed -->
```

This primarily affects interactive scenarios (live editing + kin queries in the same session). For static rendering it is not a problem.

!! 5. Field must contain a title list

The traversed field (default: `tags`) must be a standard TiddlyWiki title list. If a field contains free text or malformed bracket syntax, kin silently skips it. Single-value fields like `parent` work fine since a bare title is a valid title list of one.

!! 6. Default field is `tags`, not `parent`

If you omit the field suffix, kin uses the `tags` field:

```
<!-- These are DIFFERENT: -->
[kin[MyNode]]           <!-- traverses tags field -->
[kin:parent[MyNode]]    <!-- traverses parent field -->
```

Always specify the field explicitly when working with non-tag hierarchies.

!! 7. Combines poorly with sort — kin returns discovery order

Results come back in traversal order (breadth-first-ish). If you need alphabetical or other sorting, add an explicit sort step:

```
[kin:parent:to[MyNode]] -[<myNode>] +[sort[caption]]
```
